        <p>C. Background information </p>

<p>Note: discussed the following in this part:<br>The client, client’s family, parents, children, siblings if applicable <br>Significant others (if important or related to client’s problem/situation <br>Client’s environment (neighborhood, community: physical, social characteristics, etc.)</p>

<p>D. Underlying of Problem</p>

<p>The causes of the problem, why it happens, what are the solutions executed by the client, what are the reasons why that particular solution was not effective. </p>

<p>E. Helping Goals ( the “ends” desired example, it is write as to be achieved at the end of the helping relationship)</p>

<p>At the end of the working relationship, the worker and client will be able to:</p>

<p>1. Look for an alternative means of earning <br>2. Refer client for possible employment <br>3. Contact significant others that could temporarily assist the client in his or her current situation.</p>

<p>F. Action Plan (the “means” to achieve the defined goals, example specific interventions, activities, task that have to be done to achieve the goals) follow the format below:<br></p>
        <div contenteditable="true" class="plan" id="plan">
          <p>
            </p><p>Associated Problem 1: Insomnia<br>Interventions: </p>

<p>1. Practice good sleep hygiene: Establish a consistent sleep schedule, stick to a relaxing bedtime routine, and create a comfortable sleep environment. </p>

<p>2. Avoid stimulants: Reduce intake of caffeine and other stimulants, especially in the evening. </p>

<p>3. Mindfulness and relaxation techniques: Explore practices such as meditation, deep breathing, or progressive muscle relaxation to help unwind before sleep. </p>

<p>4. Exercise regularly: Engage in regular physical activity, preferably earlier in the day, to promote overall health and improve sleep quality. </p>

<p>5. Consider cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT): Consult with a qualified professional for CBT to address any underlying psychological factors contributing to insomnia. </p>

<p>Activities: </p>

<p>1. Maintain a consistent sleep schedule: Go to bed at the same time each day and set an alarm for the same time each morning. </p>

<p>2. Create a relaxing bedtime routine: Engage in relaxing activities before bed, such as reading or listening to soothing music. Avoid screens for at least one hour before bedtime. </p>

<p>3. Practice meditation or deep breathing: Set aside time for meditation or deep breathing exercises to help relax the body and calm the mind. </p>

<p>4. Exercise regularly: Engage in at least 30-60 minutes of moderate to vigorous activity, such as brisk walking, jogging, or any physical activity of choice. Ensure exercise is completed at least one hour before bedtime. </p>

<p>5. Consider professional help: Research psychologists or therapists who specialize in sleep disorders and Insomnia to initiate counseling or therapy if the problem persists. </p>

<p>Resources Needed: </p>

<p>1. Availability and commitment to establishing and maintaining a consistent sleep schedule. </p>

<p>2. Willingness to engage in research and experimentation with different relaxation techniques to find what works best. </p>

<p>3. Access to educational materials, online resources, and/or consulting with healthcare professionals for guidance. </p>

<p>Expected Outcome: </p>

<p>1. Improved sleep duration and quality, with a decrease in the time taken to fall asleep. </p>

<p>2. Greater sense of relaxation and reduced anxiety levels before and during the sleep process. </p>

<p>3. Improved overall health and well-being through regular exercise and effective stress management. </p>

<p>4. Reduced insomnia symptoms and improved daily performance and quality of life. </p>

<p>Associated Problem 2: Lack of Energy<br>Interventions: </p>

<p>1. Nutrition and dietary adjustments: Analyze diet and ensure a balanced intake of nutrients, including complex carbohydrates, protein, and healthy fats. Consider adding a multivitamin to the diet. </p>

<p>2. Regular exercise: Engage in regular exercise, ideally in the morning, to increase energy levels and promote overall well-being. Find an exercise activity that is enjoyable like walking, swimming, or dancing. </p>

<p>3. Manage stress: Develop stress management strategies, such as setting realistic goals, prioritizing tasks, and employing deep breathing or other relaxation techniques to alleviate stress and recharge. </p>

<p>4. Consider medical conditions: Consult with a general practitioner or healthcare professional to rule out any underlying medical conditions causing chronic fatigue. </p>

<p>Activities: </p>

<p>1. Maintain a balanced diet: Ensure each meal contains a portion of fruits and vegetables, whole grains, lean protein, and healthy fats. Keep a food diary if needed, to track nutritional intake. </p>

<p>2. Adjust diet based on nutrition needs: Include complex carbohydrates for slow-release energy and avoid big meals close to bedtime. </p>

<p>3. Exercise for at least 20-30 minutes a day: Whether it's walking, cycling, or any other enjoyable physical activity. </p>

<p>4. Manage stress: Learn to say no to commitments, avoid unrealistic deadlines, and take short breaks to recharge throughout the day. Set aside at least 15 minutes a day for relaxation practice. </p>

<p>Resources Needed: </p>

<p>1. Accessibility to a variety of nutritious food options and possibly a nutrition plan tailored to the client's needs. </p>

<p>2. Budget or insurance coverage for potential consultation with a dietician or healthcare professional. </p>

<p>3. Access to a supportive community or online resources for guidance on stress management techniques. </p>

<p>Expected Outcome: </p>

<p>1. Increased energy levels and a more vibrant daily function.</p>

<p>2. Improved ability to accomplish daily tasks and perform up to potential at work/school. </p>

<p>3. Reduced feelings of exhaustion and increased overall motivation and well-being. </p>

<p>Let me know if you would like to address any other problems!</p>
          <p></p>
